\begin_layout Title
Bragging and Hiding: Spousal Disagreement among Ugandan Maize Farmers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
To gain a better understanding of intrahousehold bargaining processes, surveys
 increasingly collect data from co-heads individually, especially on decision
 making, asset ownership and labour contributions.
 However, answers provided by spouses on the same set of questions often
 differ substantially.
 Recent research suggests that, while some of this disagreement is due to
 measurement error, part of it reflects real information asymmetry, where
 one spouse knows more than the other.
 The fact that disagreement also seems higher for assets that are easier
 to hide suggests spouses may strategically hide information from each other.
 In this paper, we test this hypothesis by checking if facilitating mutual
 monitoring reduces disagreement.
 Furthermore, we explore an alternative explanation, whereby differences
 in responses are driven by role congruity, where spouses provide answers
 that are in line with gendered norms and customs in society.
\end_layout

